	Q : What is spring IOC ? 
   ans :  Spring IoC is a container. It holds and manages the beans(Objects).It manages the life Cycle of the 
	       bean from creating a bean to dependency injection and configuring(manages the bean behaviour) that 
		   bean.
		   
		   configuration meaning - manages the bean behaviour means to provide defination to a bean(giving 
		   identification to a bean).
		   
		  IoC uses DI (Dependency Injection) to manage components like classes, services, controllers, and 
		  repositories that are annotated with @Component. Instead of using @Component, you can also use 
		  @Service, @Controller, or @Repository, which are specialized forms of @Component.
		  
		  ex : Without IoC: You go to the kitchen, cook your own meal, and serve it yourself.
               With IoC (Spring): You just tell the waiter what you want, and the kitchen (Spring) prepares and gives it
			   to you.
			   so spring io is like that it manages the bean for u. u not need to worry how it is created and all 
               
			So, Spring IoC manages the beans for you. You don’t need to worry about how they are created or managed. You
			just define what you need, and Spring takes care of creating the objects, injecting dependencies, and managing
			their lifecycle.
            
			It’s basically Spring taking control so your code is cleaner, loosely coupled, and easier to maintain.
			
           
		  Q : What is Dependency Injection ? 
		  Ans- Dependency Injection: When one bean (e.g., a @Controller class) relies on another bean 
		       (e.g., a @Service class), Spring injects the @Service bean into the @Controller bean. 
			   This allows the @Controller to use the @Service without creating it directly, making the 
			   code more flexible and easier to manage.
		      
