     Q : what are idompotent methods in spring boot ? 

       In simple terms, idempotent methods in Spring Boot (and HTTP in general) are methods that, when called 
	   multiple times with the same input, will always produce the same result and not have any additional side 
	   effects after the first call.

       Idempotent Methods in HTTP
       HTTP GET, PUT, and DELETE methods are usually considered idempotent.
       GET: Fetches data without changing anything, so calling it multiple times doesn't change the result.
       PUT: Updates or replaces a resource. Calling it multiple times with the same data will result in the same
	   state(i.e., no change after the first update).
       DELETE: Removes a resource. Calling it multiple times doesn't change the fact that the resource is deleted.

        | Method   | Idempotent?  | Meaning                                                      |
        | -------- | -----------  | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
        | `GET`    | ✅ Yes       | Read data — calling it 1 time or 100 times is same           |
        | `PUT`    | ✅ Yes       | Update data — setting the same value repeatedly              |
        | `DELETE` | ✅ Yes       | Deleting the same item again does nothing (after first time) |


        Non-Idempotent Methods
        HTTP POST is typically not idempotent because it usually creates a new resource. If you call it multiple 
		times, you may create multiple resources, changing the system's state.
		
		| Method  | Non-Idempotent?  | Meaning                                                        |
        | ------  | ---------------  | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
        | `POST`  | ✅ Yes           | Used to **create** new data — multiple calls create duplicates |
		| `PATCH` |  Usually Yes     | Used to partially update data — repeated calls may change data again and again |
		
		⚠️ PATCH is usually non-idempotent, but not always:

		-> If your patch adds 10 points, it changes each time → ✅ non-idempotent.

		-> But if the patch says set score to 50, calling it again does nothing → ❌ idempotent.
				
        PATCH is typically non-idempotent, because it may apply incremental changes. But it can be idempotent depending 
		on how the patch is designed. 

        Why is it Important?
        Idempotency ensures reliability and predictability in your API, especially for scenarios like retries 
		(e.g., if the request fails but the operation should still be safe to repeat).
        In summary, idempotent methods always produce the same result if invoked multiple times with the same 
		input, and they don’t cause unintended changes after the first call.
		
