Q21 : what is n+1 problem in hibernate ? 
Ans : 
The N+1 problem happens when Hibernate first runs 1 query to get the main data (like a list of hotels), and 
then runs N more queries to get related data (like rooms for each hotel).

So if you have 10 hotels, it runs 1 + 10 = 11 queries instead of just 1 or 2.
This makes your app slow and inefficient.

You can fix it using JOIN FETCH to fetch everything in one go.

Q22 : what is JOIN FETCH  ?
Ans : 

how n+1 problems looks like :  
Repository Method that causes N+1 Problem:
// HotelRepository.java
@Query("SELECT h FROM Hotel h")
List<Hotel> findAllHotels();

Service Layer (causes N+1)
List<Hotel> hotels = hotelRepository.findAllHotels();

for (Hotel hotel : hotels) {
    System.out.println(hotel.getName());

    //This line triggers a separate SQL query for each hotel's rooms
    System.out.println("Rooms: " + hotel.getRooms().size());
}

Use JOIN FETCH to solve it 
@Query("SELECT h FROM Hotel h JOIN FETCH h.rooms")
List<Hotel> findAllHotelsWithRooms();


List<Hotel> hotels = hotelRepository.findAllHotelsWithRooms();

for (Hotel hotel : hotels) {
    System.out.println(hotel.getName());
    System.out.println("Rooms: " + hotel.getRooms().size()); // ✅ No extra queries now
}

| Without `JOIN FETCH` | Causes N+1 problem (many DB hits)               |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| With `JOIN FETCH`    | Solves it by fetching everything in one query ✅|


