Q21 : life cycle of hibernate ? 
Ans : 
| Stage | Name         | Meaning                                                                                                                        |
| ----- | -------------| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| 1️⃣   | **Transient**  | Object is just created using `new`, **not saved** in DB, **not tracked** by Hibernate.                                         |
| 2️⃣   | **Persistent** | Object is saved using `session.save()` or `session.persist()` — now **Hibernate tracks it** and manages updates automatically. |
| 3️⃣   | **Detached**   | Session is closed → object is **no longer tracked** by Hibernate, but still exists in memory.                                  |
| 4️⃣   | **Removed**    | Object is **deleted** from DB using `session.delete()` — no longer in DB or tracked.                                           |


// 1️⃣ Transient — Just created, not in DB
User user = new User();
user.setName("Saurav");

// 2️⃣ Persistent — Saved and tracked by Hibernate
Session session = factory.openSession();
session.beginTransaction();

session.save(user);  // Hibernate now manages this object

session.getTransaction().commit();

// 3️⃣ Detached — Session closed, Hibernate stops tracking it
session.close();

// 4️⃣ Removed — Deleted from DB using a new session
Session newSession = factory.openSession();
newSession.beginTransaction();

newSession.delete(user); // Object is now removed from DB

newSession.getTransaction().commit();
newSession.close();


how it works internally it is like this  

### 💡 What really happens:

When you do:

```java
User user = new User();  
user.setName("Saurav");
```

👉 This object is **Transient** — it exists **only in Java memory**, not in the database.

---

### Then:

```java
session.save(user);
session.getTransaction().commit();
```

👉 Now Hibernate **inserts** this record into the **database**.
So after the commit — ✅ **the user is saved in DB** and becomes **Persistent**.

---

### Next:

```java
session.close();
```

👉 The Hibernate session is closed — now Hibernate **stops tracking** this object.
So it becomes **Detached**, but the **record is still present in the database**.

---

### Finally:

```java
newSession.delete(user);
newSession.getTransaction().commit();
```

👉 Hibernate deletes that **existing DB record** (because it uses the object’s ID).
After commit, the record is **removed from the database** — so now it’s in the **Removed** state.

---

### 🧠 In short:

| **State**      | **Meaning (Very Simple Words)**                                                         |
| -------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Transient**  | Object is created **in Java only**, **not in DB**, and **Hibernate does not track it**. |
| **Persistent** | Object is **saved in DB** and **Hibernate is tracking it** inside an open session.      |
| **Detached**   | Session is **closed**, object still exists in DB, but **Hibernate stops tracking it**.  |
| **Removed**    | Hibernate is instructed to **delete the object from DB**.                               |


---

So the key idea 🔑:

> The object **is deleted from the database only if it was previously saved (persistent)**.
> If you try to `delete()` a **transient** object (not saved), Hibernate will throw an error — because it doesn’t exist
  in DB yet.



