The @ResponseBody annotation in Spring tells the framework to directly send the return value of a method as the 
HTTP response body. It means that instead of rendering a view (like a webpage), the method's return value 
(e.g., JSON or plain text) is sent directly to the client.	

ResponseEntity is a class in Spring that represents the entire HTTP response, including the status code, headers, and body.			 

ResponseEntity is a class in Spring that helps you build HTTP responses. It allows you to set the status code, headers, and body of the response.

In your example:

java
Copy code
@GetMapping
public ResponseEntity<List<Registration>> getAllReg() {
    List<Registration> registrations = registrationRepository.findAll();
    return new ResponseEntity<List<Registration>>(registrations, HttpStatus.OK);
}
ResponseEntity<List<Registration>>: Represents the entire HTTP response, including the list of Registration objects and the HTTP status code.
new ResponseEntity<>(registrations, HttpStatus.OK): Constructs the response with the body (registrations) and status code (HttpStatus.OK), which means the request was successful.
So, ResponseEntity lets you customize the HTTP response sent to the client.								

Here’s a simple explanation of the difference between @RequestBody and @ResponseBody in Spring:

1. @RequestBody:
Purpose: Binds the HTTP request body to a method parameter in a controller.
Use Case: When a client sends data (e.g., JSON) to your server, @RequestBody converts that data into a Java object.
Example:

java
Copy code
@PostMapping("/addUser")
public String addUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    // The HTTP request body is converted to a User object
    return "User added!";
}
2. @ResponseBody:
Purpose: Converts the Java method return value into the HTTP response body.
Use Case: When you want to send data (e.g., JSON or text) directly as a response to the client, without rendering a view.
Example:

java
Copy code
@GetMapping("/getUser")
@ResponseBody
public User getUser() {
    // The returned User object will be converted to JSON (or XML) and sent as the response body
    return new User("John", "Doe");
}
Key Difference:
@RequestBody: Takes data from the client (request body) and converts it to a Java object.
@ResponseBody: Sends data from the server (method return value) as the HTTP response body.

